INERT FIXTURE — DO NOT EXECUTE OR UPLOAD TO A REAL SERVER
Purpose: tests that upload handlers reject files whose true type (PHP script) does not match
the declared extension (.jpg) — both the TYPE/TRANSPORT layer (magic-byte check) and the
CONTENT/RENDER layer (PHP code in a file served as an image) should produce findings.
Threat: if a web server is misconfigured (e.g. Apache mod_php processes .php in filenames
regardless of final extension), this file executes as PHP even though it ends in .jpg.
The double-extension attack bypasses simple extension-only checks.
Control: validate MIME type via magic bytes server-side, never by extension alone;
store uploaded files outside the webroot or with a generated non-executable name.

Payload representation (inert, open tag intentionally absent to prevent PHP parsing):
  [php-open-tag] echo "INERT: this content should never be executed"; [php-close-tag]
